Black holes don't destroy mass, they acquire it. So when two black holes collide, you just get one, bigger black hole. You can think of it as the larger one absorbing the smaller, but unless there's a huge size difference, it's more of a mutual event. The energy calculations are due to the way mass/energy is released upon crossing the event horizon, I believe. When matter crosses the event horizon, some of it flashes away as high energy waves; if you have two /massive/ objects colliding, a lot of energy would be released. As to how the calculated how much energy, I have no idea. They have years of higher math, I have one.
